s are perpetuated through policy, and how Peruvians’ everyday pursuits of state-sanctioned domestic ideals reproduce informality and landscapes of poverty in the urban periphery. The only full-length ethnography written about Lima’s iconic and policy-inspiring shantytowns in thirty years, Unruly Domestication provides valuable insight into the dynamics of housing and urban development in the Global South, elucidating the most intimate and profound effects of global efforts to do good.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBureaucracyzPeruzLima. 0aPoorzPeruzLima. 0aPovertyxGovernment policyzPeruzLima. 0aPovertyxSocial aspectszPeruzLima. 0aSingle motherszPeruzLimaxSocial conditions. 0aSquatter settlementsxSocial aspectszPeruzLima. 0aSquatterszPeruzLimaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aLima, Peru, Latin America, ethnography, marginality, development, urban, housing, extreme poverty zones, informality, statecraft, politics, bureaucracy, property, formalization, kinship, family, gender.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32909240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477329115/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles